Dear Jojo , I know exactly how he feels . I was first given a cancer diagnosis in april 2012 and didnt recieve any ""treatment"" until september ( 2012 ), the best part of six months later . All I wanted was to get stuck into treatment but all I seemed to get was one biopsy or scan after the other then a final attempt at surgery before they finally set me off on chemo . Frustrating as it was I have to accept that the reason was to try to ascertain the ""precise and exact"" cancer they are going to treat . In my case , the cells from the tumour on my lung gave a ""medical indicator"" that it had originated , biologically , in my gut and my oncologist needed to be certain he was treating the primary cause rather than the secondary . So he spent some time with endoscopies and scans looking for something he never did find . However , if it had been there and he had missed it then things could have been far worse for me than the delay caused by the search for it . Be assured , there is no system based on ""how someone reports how they feel themselves"". I have hardly ever felt better in my life than I do now (or happier ), yet I am now on palliative programme with a terminal diagnosis . This is far from a logical illness but you and your father have my understanding and best wishes . Tones

My dad was given a break too when his scans revealed only a very small evidence of cancer in his left lung and and the two small lesions on his liver . I hated the fact that he wasn't getting chemo and that it might grow back double in 30 days . I was scared to say the least , but his body need a break and he had gotten so sick . The Dr . gave him another scan in 4 weeks and the cancer in his lung was GONE and the liver mets were very small . My dad got to enjoy a three 1/2 month break and recouperation period before his recurrence in March . Point is , you never know how a person is going to react to after treatment is over , or during a break , or if the chemo continues to work . Just consider what the Dr . is saying , and know that it can be beat if it is closely monitored . Second opinions could not hurt , then again , maybe her doctor could monitor with x-rays inbetween the ct scans like my dad was . I am SO HAPPY your moms results were SO GOOD ! I will continue to pray that they stay good and only get BETTER ! (( HUGS ))

Hi Brian When I had my initial x-ray that led to the cancer diagnosis , the hospital emailed the x-ray to the GP surgery that same day and the surgery rang me to advise me that they had made an urgent appointment for me to see GP the next working day ( which was a Monday ). That was a fun weekend ! If the radiographer had seen something of concern in the x-ray the surgery would have been notified as a matter of urgency . Look at it as a positive that the surgery has not called you . To put your mind at rest , ring the surgery when it re-opens after the Christmas break and ask to speak to a GP . I know that waiting can be difficult but remember that worrying never changes anything . Stay off the ciggies and try to enjoy Christmas . x

At the request of one of the forum members in the thread , the following information on oil specification has been provided by ""oilman"" -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Most oils have both petrol and diesel ratings which are labelled by their API or ACEA ratings . The ratings are as follows but at those prices , you'll be getting what you pay for . API = American Petroleum Institute S = Service - Petrol Engine Performance C = Commercisl - Diesel Engine Performance PETROL SG - Introduced 1989 has much more active dispersant to combat black sludge . SH - Introduced 1993 has same engine tests as SG , but includes phosphorus limit 0 . 12%, together with control of foam , volatility and shear stability . SJ - Introduced 1996 has the same engine tests as SG/SH , but phosphorus limit 0 . 10% together with variation on volatility limits SL - Introduced 2001 , all new engine tests reflective of modern engine designs meeting current emmissions standards DIESEL CD - Introduced 1955 , international standard for turbo diesel engine oils for many years , uses single cylinder test engine only CE - Introduced 1984 , improved control of oil consumption , oil thickening , piston deposits an wear , uses additional multi cylinder test engines CF4 - Introduced 1990 , further improvements in control of oil consumption and piston deposits , uses low emmission test engine CF - Introduced 1994 , modernised version of CD , reverts to single cylinder low emission test engine . Intended for certain indirect injection engines CF2 - Introduced 1994 , defines effective control of cylinder deposits and ring face scuffing , intended for 2 stroke diesel engines CG4 - Introduced 1994 , development of CF4 giving improved control of piston deposits , wear , oxidation stability and soot entrainment . Uses low sulphur diesel fuel in engine tests CH4 - Introduced 1998 , development of CG4 , giving further improvements in control of soot related wear and piston deposits , uses more comprehensive engine test program to include low and high sulphur fuelsSG - Introduced 1989 has much more active dispersant to combat black sludge . ACEA Specifications ( Association des Constructeurs Europeens d ? Automobiles ) ACEA ratings are prefixed with ? A ? for petrol , ? B ? for light or passenger car diesel and ? E ? for heavy duty diesel . The current specifications are A1 Fuel economy petrol A2 Standard performance level A3 High performance and/or extended drain A4 Reserved for future use in certain direct injection engines A5 Combines A1 fuel economy with A3 performance B1 Fuel economy diesel B2 Standard performance level B3 High performance and/or extended drain B4 For direct injection car diesel engines B5 Combines B1 fuel economy with B3/B4 performance E1 Non-turbocharged light duty diesel engines E2 Standard performance level E3 High performance and extended drain E4 Higher performance and longer extended drain E5 High performance and long drain plus API performances Cheers Simon

Hi Omega ; Nobody really knows for sure when someone¬ís time will be up . There is so much out there now to help patients with cancer that I feel it is difficult to see a timeline . Some people are more apt to give up with a time frame or depress them more . On the other hand , it seems fair a person should know . This one will be between you and the family I suppose . We are still dealing with that one . I do agree that some patients can handle being told a timeline , but some cannot . How that is determined , I do not yet know . To read a timeline is worse than the doctor telling it . Careful what you read and where you read . Getting additional opinions is excellent . I am not so sure you should be considering what treatments but see what the options are for treatment . Let them inform you . There are a number of Stage 4 patients , and my husband is currently one , that get palliative care . It won¬ít cure it but it can prolong it . Some don¬ít go for a long time but others pull extra years . There will be various choices . I have a niece going into a third year . I think it was kind of explained to us that the treatments are good if the quantity of qualify life is met . The patient decides if X number of days a week is worth whatever the reactions are to the meds . My husband , I think , will do better now that the radiation is over . If you keep reading here , you will see that . I may be wrong but I always thought Stage 4 was never surgery . They can explain this to you . If you want to read , do some reading here . I found this very helpful to me . I think you are on the right track . My husband had same lung cancer and after very aggressive radiation and chemo , it was successful enough that they were able to remove his two lower lobes of his right lung . He was Stage 3B then . All was fine until this past October and it is back and now he is Stage 4 . The link in my sig tells about his journey . It is a little long but you could glance over it . It was a tough road for him but he made . They couldn¬ít radiate his lungs again but they did his spine this time and chemo for the lungs . Fortunately the recent PetScan shows things improved but still one lymph node lights up and some very small ones that questionable even if they are cancer . They are continuing with more chemo . For what it is it is good . At some point , you might find that you will want to salvage all the good times you can with Dad while he is feeling well . I did that today with my husband . Next week he may not feel so good . It is not an easy road but coming here can be encouraging . Don¬ít forget about this part . Time together . Now you have a couple points of view . Amounts to the same in different words . I ramble on . PBJ is so good with words . I will have your Dad in my thoughts and prayers . Keep us posted . Remember , second is good to get , if even just for your own piece of mind .

Sorry , this is really long but I have to get it off my chest My Dad was diagnosed with nsclc a year ago . He underwent chemo & radio and was told at his 12 month check-up that he had another tumor in his lung which was eating into his rib . He reported his headaches & sickness at this point which we had all put down to stress . Consultant said she wanted to rule out anything untoward in his head , so referred him for scans & second round of radio . Week before his radio started I rang him to see how he was & he seemed to be slurring ; Dad's not one to fuss and only when I pushed him he said he thought he might have had a mini stroke ! Frantically got him a Dr appointment who diagnosed Bell's Palsy due to a numbness in his tongue . He was admitted to University Hospital North Durham for tests & obs . Biggest joke is , I came up from my home in Leicester for that week to take him for his radio at the Freeman in Newcastle- I had to pick him up from hospital in Durham , take him for treatment at Newcastle & deliver him back to Durham - all because they couldn't get transport sorted ! 3 hour round trips for a week ! While he was in hospital he had a CT scan , the lung function nurse gave him the results of this as ""all clear - nothing on his brain"" On the last day of his treatment , whilst he was away from the ward in Durham , a porter came to take him for his MRI scan and couldn't as Dad was in Newcastle having radio . Consultant came in afternoon and was visibly pi**ed off at Dad having missed the scan , so discharged him ""as he may as well wait for an appointment as an outpatient"". 5 weeks later and Dad has MRI scan , still no follow up appointment for the results . After ringing the Consultants secretary for over a week , I manage to blag an appointment for Sept 7th . Sept 7th comes , we are told that cancer has spread to Dad's head and is pressing on the Hypoglossal nerve which has caused his tongue to go numb . surgery is not an option due to the risk it carries and the fact that the disease is so aggressive , if they remove the tumor , another is likely to grow in it's place . Chemo can't be given and radio not possible due to the damage it may cause to the surrounding nerves ... Dad asks how long and is told 3mth - 3 year . Consultant thinks Dad shouldn't be getting headaches from the tumor and wants him to have a lumber puncture to test the meningal fluid . ( methinks there may be more tumors up there now ). By now , Dad is hardly eating , at 18stoone Dad not eating is unusual to say the least . Lung Function nurse tells consultant ( yes , TELLS ) to try anti-sickness drugs and not to admit Dad . We leave hospital with script for anti-sickness drugs & told mac nurse will bring morphine . 8th Sept- Dad still vomitting & headache worse than ever . I chase up lung function nurse , she will make sure referrals are done 9th Sept- see above . I call Dad's GP and tell him he needs something for pain , GP calls Dad to say script ready for morphine . 10th Sept - hurrah ! Dad is no longer in pain ! This is the very short version of what has happened . I have quit my job in Leicester , got my flat up for rent to move home at 38 to look after him & Mam who has severe heart failure . I have had to fight EVERY STEP OF THE WAY to get Dad seen & treated . Dad thinks it's because he's 60 and on the scrap heap they aren't bothered and I have to say that despite disagreeing with him face to face , I agree totally . I know he is dying and they can't stop that , but the NHS and their treatment of my Dad ( don't get me started on Mam's experience ) is a disgrace . I know that staff working in the NHS are doing a tough job and are incredible for the most part , but I am so disappointed that I had to air my thoughts with someone other than my fantastic family & friends . PS - any stories on the mts to the brain would be useful . Shelle

On Windows , you get the SpotifyWebHelper . exe loaded , no matter what . It always creates an entry in the startup list and loads in the background , regardless of the client's setting on auto-loading being at 'no'. Once you run Spotify , you get the startup back . Since I'm using another client ( Fidelify ) I can safely state that this sort of 'helper' application isn't needed , especially not when the user sets it to off and/or doesn't even start the service . I don't like it when programs disregard their own settings and force-load modules without notice and need . Why not start and end services with the main application ? Current rough workaround delete (or better rename ) the exe , Spotify works like before . If it doesn't , just revert back . I wrote about the significant RAM impact before . For just playing some music , most likely while you are using some 'main' applications , 400mb or more aren't justifiable in principle . This becomes even more obvious when looking at how many features got lost with updating . So there's no automatic volume adjustment , same as there are no apps running within the client or simple search/navigate features . Again , the most striking comparison can be made when firing up a basic Spotify client ( mentioned above ) and looking how responsive the UI and streaming presents itself , with not even using 60mb , while offering search filters . On a side note , one does not get the ASIO/WASAPI audio interface with Spotify , while the smaller and leaner client offers it . Once you've heard the difference , this lack , especially for premium users ( HQ streaming ), becomes quite apparent in the sense of wondering why a music service is avoiding the better sound output while already streaming the necessary file sizes . On another occasion , one could define and set the cache location and size . Now you can't . While you still can't pick where to actually install the Spotify client ( it grabs AppDataRoamingSpotify on Windows , no matter what ), it now caches and uses that same location which isn't what some SSD users might have planned for their precious free space . Those music files do not benefit from any SSD speeds . Thanks for keeping track of all the losses coming with the new client in the threads like these . With every day adding to the life of the new and reduced client , it seems harder to stick with the otherwise fine service . I actually like the Android client ( and sound ) a lot more than the current Windows software .

First , welcome to out site , we are glad to have you here . Second we are not medically trained unless the writer says so , so take our advice with a large spoon full of caution . Your high blood pressure needs to be treated less your kidneys fail or you have a stroke or heart attack . Please see a doctor soon as that is a real problem .Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension , PAH , is a disease of high blood pressure in the arterial chamber between the right ventricle of the heart and the lung . From all I have read and been told and experienced personally , high body blood pressure has no relationship to PAH . That is one or the other can be high and the other low . Or they can both be high or both low . This is not a disease that you want as there is no cure . The only way to absolutely diagnose it is to use a catheter and directly measure the pressure in the arterial chamber . Then if its over 25 or so , you have PAH by definition . It is a rare disease and it is a high probability as a doctor if you tell someone they don't have it you are right . It is not a disease where you want to say that you do have it unless you have made the measurement . Even an electrocardiogram is only an estimate of yes or no you have it . So Don't stress so much if at all possible . Get your BP under control and then if you are still anxious see a GP and get a pill or two and laugh and be happy . No worthwhile doctor is going to subject you to a heart catherization unless there is every possibility that you do have a problem there . God have mercy on us allKeep in touch and let us hear from you . Best regardsCicero

For a diesel , the start is the hard bit ! Because compression ignition engines rely on the heat of compression to initiate combustion , they can be quite picky about starting ! The ""heat"" bit comes from the compression , so leaky rings , slow cranking or incorrect valve timing all can reduce that bitThe ""fuel"" bit requires nicely atomised fuel in the correct quantities . Large droplets of fuel , caused by low rail pressure at start or worn injector nozzles , are difficult to heat up , and tend to stick to the cold walls of the cylinder . And worse , if the cylinder fails to fire on the first few turns , the injector keeps on pumping in more fuel , which cools the cylinder even more , making it even less likely to fire ! And when it does , all the liquid diesel gets chucked out into the exhaust and burnt at low pressure and temperaure , effectively creating a smoke screen out back ! So , here are the test you need to do BEFORE you spend any money changing stuff1 ) Check glow plugs - done ! 2 ) Check it cranks at a decent speed ( no knackered battery or stater motor ) 3 ) Do a cold cranking compression test4 ) Log , ideally using an OBD tool , the fuel rail pressure prior to , during , and after a start event . You could also use a multimeter to read the pressure sensor output , but it's not ideal , as you want to see pressure vs engine speed . ( worn HP pumps are less efective at low speed , leading to low rail pressures at cranking ) 5 ) If that all looks normal , out with the injectors and get them tested and re-conditionedMost people , just throw a new set of injectors at the problem BEFORE they work out what is actually wrong with it , It could be as simple as a failing rail pressure sensor or lift pump ...

They started at ... the end of January , start of February . I think mid Feb our family doctor tries to get him an MRI and the insurance company says no because she ""didn't give a good enough reason"". Gave him antibiotics because they thought it was allergies . Ugh . I realize foresight is in play here but ... still . How did his doctors let him go three months with painful headaches and a host of other problems ( slight vision issues , slight dizziness , etc ) without trying harder to convince the insurance company he needed an MRI ? They might be able to alter the mix of GPU resources to heavily emphasize pixel processing while leaving the number of polygons , detail of textures , and instructions that can be decoded the same . 2 . Mums Palliative Chemotherapy was a complete disaster ! She was violently sick for 3 solid days and ended up in hospital . To cut a very long ( two months ) story short , mum has been in hospital 3 times since Feb , she has haemorrhaged and is now living with us . She has tumours in both lungs , womb secondary tumour , and now brain secondary tumour , she is exhausted , confused , thin , and I feel I have lost the mum I knew , she is my best friend and I am devastated . I care for her every day , she can just get up out of bed , and walk to the lounge and she is exhausted . The doctors have said she is in the 'weeks to live' category , as opposed to months or days . She gets worse every week . Today , she walked into the lounge and hit the floor . A complete blackout , is this normal with a brain tumour ? Every day is sad , sad to see her look like she does , and sad because she is no longer able to do so many things . She has talked about her funeral , her belongings , and her wishes . It breaks my heart . Can anyone tell me their experiences of secondary lung cancer in the brain . I am frightened she will lose all faculties and not be able to communicate . This cancer has gone on for almost 5 years now , and every year something more devastating happens . Hospitals have now said make her comfortable at home , they cannot do anything for her , my doctors have said they are on the end of the phone if I need them , the district nurses call in every week , and keep telling me to let them help , she doesnt want them to , she wants me to do every thing , it is so tiring for me as I am disabled with arthritis , and the stress is making the arthritis worse . I feel the doctors and district nurses think its me being independant , but it isnt , its mum she doesnt want people around her , only me , my husband and my son . My heart goes out to any of you in the same situation , its upsetting , tiring , and very very sad . Ronnie xx

Can you file the stub clean enough to slide the carrier off what remains of the bolt ? Things will be easier if so . I would then clean-up the bolt stub with wirewool/dremel and find someone with a MIG welder and have them weld an M10 or sim nut to the stub . Wind it out immediately while hot - it should come free owing to the welding heat dumped into the stub . I've had broken studs out of more-awkward things ( eg snapped flush with engine block ...) before by this method . If not at first try , hit the migged stub with a torch , try again , - until it comes free .
